skos:Concept.skos:scopeNote: {"id": "359879a4-b349-4782-82ae-bce485cfc185", "value": "Twin-engined jet-fighter. The first British aircraft to exceed Mach 1 in level flight, later to exceed Mach 2. Entered service in 1960. After 13 years was superseded in its primary defence role by the Phantom, though remained in RAF service until 1988."}

{"id": "0a53b3bc-2cfe-4ac4-969e-4077d8525d89", "value": "The RAF's first jet fighter, flown operationally during 1944-5, with later versions serving for a further ten years after the war. The Meteor's first active operations were in the interception and destruction of V.1. flying bombs."}

{"id": "d2cf6dba-14e2-4105-89ce-7d10d17c871a", "value": "Four-engine, long range heavy bomber. Developed from the Lancaster, and originally designated the Lancaster Mk. IV, it was larger in size, bombload and fuel capacity. Never used operationally in World War Two."}
{"id": "9a85260c-8f1f-4c2e-9217-18deb909a26d", "value": "A twin engined advanced trainer aircraft developed for the military by the US firm of Cessna"}
{"id": "515aa8ba-a120-427a-9cc5-989eff51c439", "value": "American, all-metal-construction, fighter. Entered service in 1941. 209 were delivered to RAF/FAA, most of which were used in the Far East."}

{"id": "e1f26163-9825-4f10-a401-0513768eee3b", "value": "Impressed civil, twin-engined airliner converted to a military transport. Thirty were ordered for military use, though only eleven were actually built. Entered service in 1940, with the last being scrapped in 1950."}

{"id": "b9bd9308-9db9-42f3-9470-891e8d087b29", "value": "British single-engine, two-seat night fighter. Originally intended as a day fighter, but withdrawn and converted in August 1940, this was the first fighter to incorporate a power-driven gun turret."}

{"id": "58f18386-c812-47fb-a297-2aa852a5d6be", "value": "Twin-engined bomber. The Whitley was the first 'heavy' bomber to be built in quantity for the RAF and made the first bombing attack on Germany in May 1940. It was later used for convoy protection and reconnaissance."}

{"id": "edca2bb0-8fbd-4e14-afa9-6ef27062d364", "value": "Single-seat, single-engine fighter-bomber: Curtiss P40 Warhawk, known to the RAF as the Tomahawk, later renamed Kittyhawk. Serving from 1941 to 1942, control difficulties in dive attacks impeded bombing accuracy, resulting in use for larger targets only."}

{"id": "7e865456-4b68-4371-b8ca-d62a3a970efc", "value": "Post-World War Two, single-engine, high-wing utility transport. Manufactured by De Havilland Canada, was also produced in a seaplane version. Known as the U6A from 1962."}

{"id": "da55c634-a82b-4220-bd43-d4e95aa6a812", "value": "American twin-engined medium bomber. Entered service with the US 22nd Bombardment Group at Langley Field in February 1941. Also served with the 14th and 39th RAF squadrons."}

{"id": "fe1bcef2-497b-4acf-841c-205f80282adf", "value": "Single-seat, single-engine fighter-bomber. Fitted with eight fixed forward-firing machine guns in the wings, plus two 1000lb bombs or six rocket projectiles."}

{"id": "28c274e9-335b-40fe-897a-e8bf72d12f54", "value": "A single-engine dive-bomber, the JU87 was very successful during the invasions of Poland and France but suffered heavy losses during the Battle of Britain. Withdrawn from NW Europe in 1941 for use in the Mediterranean and on the Eastern Front."}

{"id": "5d343349-34a3-4241-872a-744ceb812b58", "value": "Originally designed as a wood and steel bomber-reconnaissance aircraft, subsequent variations served as special transports, glider tugs and paratroop carriers. Featured a tricycle-style undercarriage."}

{"id": "fb6a2506-5ab3-42ee-8eeb-cc7b254ff729", "value": "Three-seat, single engine, high wing braced monoplane designed for civil use and first flown in 1929. Saw military service in World War 2 in an Army co-operation and communications role."}

{"id": "48bc88b4-e8a5-4263-932e-6391c4ab1301", "value": "Developed as a long range, heavy day-fighter, the ME110 found its niche as a night fighter. It saw service over Southern and Eastern England during the Battle of Britain but lost out in the daytime to the faster British fighters."}

{"id": "d51bb5e7-f6ca-4c59-b7f5-fa08b9b7f935", "value": "Single-seat, single-engine fighter-bomber and ground-attack aircraft. Entered service with the Luftwaffe in mid-1941. Approximately 20,000 were constructed between 1941 and the end of the war."}

{"id": "c0568aa9-6231-4dc1-aa71-1e739c5ac2cb", "value": "American A-20 twin-engined, light, day bomber. Some supplied to the RAF and known as the Boston I. Subsequent variations adapted to night flying and re-christened the Havoc."}

{"id": "0b4c4fc8-dc8c-4e9f-a29a-00f286b86d24", "value": "Single-engine, single-seat fighter. Entered service in 1943 as a land-based fighter. Converted to a carrierborne fighter in 1944 for use by US Navy and Fleet Air Arm. Mostly saw action in the Pacific and Far East."}

{"id": "864f4243-dc44-40d6-9a40-9c786905295a", "value": "Twin-engined, four-seat medium bomber. A re-engined variant of the Hampden, less than 200 were built but never became operational due to engine unreliability. Some were converted to Hampdens."}

{"id": "f62dd528-8fdc-4970-9bbc-c48b5dc78140", "value": "Single-engine, advanced-pilot trainer. Spruce and plywood in construction, entered service in 1939, continuing to serve as a trainer, and also a target tug, until 1950."}

{"id": "0d685bdc-c407-42c6-ab40-307c0ac92c1b", "value": "Four-engine, seven-crew heavy bomber. Entered service with RAF Bomber Command in 1940, becoming one of the twin sources of bomber strength along with the Lancaster. Also used for transport and glider tug duties."}

{"id": "2e30e06b-cbbb-4ebf-8a63-fc062232fc9c", "value": "Two-seat, twin-engined light/medium bomber celebrated for its speed and versatility. Entering service in 1941, was also adapted for duties as a fighter-bomber, Pathfinder, mine-layer, transport, trainer and photo-reconnaissance aircraft."}

{"id": "368672ab-c35c-4c88-872e-b7d58768d43d", "value": "American, single-engine fighter designed for operation from US Naval aircraft carriers. Produced between 1940 and 1945, Wildcats provided to the British Fleet Air Arm were renamed Martlets."}

{"id": "dc973bae-7ef8-467f-a8d3-16e95d9a67a8", "value": "Two-seat, twin-engined fighter/fighter-bomber designed as a replacement for the Bf110. Of the 600 or so produced, only 258 reached the Luftwaffe due to serious design faults. The ME210 was superseded by the ME410 Hornisse."}

{"id": "db88dd3e-418f-4704-bce2-0d1ca0050e0f", "value": "Single-engine navigation trainer and communications aircraft. Constructed of tubular steel and duralumin frame, with a duralumin and canvas covering, 500 were delivered to the FAA, serving from 1944-5."}

{"id": "e4d90aa8-9d11-49c8-bc79-768003889191", "value": "Fleet Air Arm fighter and torpedo-bomber, designed for operation from aircraft carriers. All-metal in construction, it entered service in 1944 and was rendered obsolete after the war by the advent of the jet aircraft."}

{"id": "48e06910-2ba0-43bb-b72b-8e9a2b24d588", "value": "Twin-engined maritime-reconnaissance bomber adapted from pre-war American airliners, the A-28 and A-29, evident from the row of portholes along its fuselage. Entered service with RAF Coastal Command just before the outbreak of World War Two."}

{"id": "61bb6429-ed3a-4941-8abe-31864884c3fe", "value": "American, four-engined, medium/heavy day bomber. Entered service in 1937. The prototype was nicknamed the Flying Fortress, which later became a registered trademark."}

{"id": "b1764b0d-16b7-42b3-8a00-b289ebfd9638", "value": "Originally ordered as land based dive-bombers, with 950 being delivered to the RAF, none are known to have flown operationally, instead apparently serving as target tugs. Bermuda was the name given to the Brewster SB2A Buccaneer in RAF service."}

{"id": "8a8d773c-b2dc-47bd-adfb-eea810fc93cf", "value": "Single-engine, single-seat fighter manufactured by Messerschmitt. First used as part of Germany's Condor legion during the Spanish Civil War, the 'one-o-nine' was the Luftwaffe's most widely used fighter seeing service throughout World War II."}

{"id": "f9047ad9-5af1-4583-aae7-69b0ce1dd6e3", "value": "American troop and supply-glider constructed from steel tube and fabric-covered wood, with a hinged nose to allow loading and unloading of troops or light vehicles. Also known as the Haig, this was the only US glider to see combat service."}

{"id": "7be13780-e92d-47e2-9c31-1f036c9dc2c6", "value": "Three-seat, twin-engined minelaying, torpedo-bombing and reconnaissance twin-float seaplane. First flown in 1936, in 1938 it set eight world speed records for its class in various range and payload categories."}

{"id": "79add165-e4cc-42ea-956c-d9ce03843001", "value": "A single engine, jet propelled twin boom aircraft which came into service in 1945 in a variety of roles including night fighter, trainer, the carrier-borne Sea Vampire, and the MK5 version, a fighter bomber. Produced by De Havilland."}

{"id": "ce265566-7ac1-4f71-83f0-d4e46be5508e", "value": "A twin-engined, multi-role aircraft built by Junkers. Originally designed as a medium bomber with the speed of a fighter, but its adaptability allowed it to fulfil the roles of night fighter, torpedo-bomber, anti-tank aircraft and photo-reconnaissance."}

{"id": "e3f2ecea-cf6a-4d2f-881b-72180289355e", "value": "A progressive development of the DO17, the twin-engined DO217 entered service in 1941. The DO217 saw service as a bomber over the UK and took part in the 'Baedecker' raids of 1942."}
{"id": "19febc58-1426-4c8b-a191-03af082d36f3", "value": "A twin engine advanced trainer developed by Beech/ Beechcraft , a US firm, used in WWII"}

{"id": "757e0d13-f186-473a-8380-b87580ef75f1", "value": "Two-crew, twin-engined bomber. Entered production in 1934 and designed for dual use as a high-speed commercial transport. Technical problems hindered its use as a bomber and led to conversion to high-altitude reconnaissance."}

{"id": "71eafb15-e8dd-46b3-b4f5-5aa4d37a61dd", "value": "Twin-engined, four-seat torpedo-bomber designed to replace the Vildebeest. Entered service with RAF Coastal Command in 1939. Later versions incorporated a remote-controlled machine gun with periscope sight."}

{"id": "baf87db6-428b-44c5-b2d0-6fd1dab3c589", "value": "The main German, medium bomber of the war, the HE111 first saw action during the Spanish Civil War. HE111s took part in the Battle of Britain and from 1944 onwards were used to launch airborne flying bombs against London."}

{"id": "c8cdd651-f0ac-4dc4-ba5b-e1ec2cba5276", "value": "Single-seat carrierborne jet fighter. Originally conceived as an RAF land-fighter, entered Fleet Air Arm service in 1951 and was the first jet fighter to be standardised in first-line squadrons."}
{"id": "e833fca7-dffb-4941-aa9a-8f2cdb413bc4", "value": "An aircraft with a single wing, or plane, either side of its fuselage."}

{"id": "54734017-7fae-4fbc-8d81-5baa7dc9574d", "value": "Troop and general transport glider. Almost entirely wooden in construction, many were manufactured by the furniture industry. Mk I featured a a door-ramp on the port side whilst the Mk II was fitted with a hinged nose."}

{"id": "9fed2bce-f43d-4d8d-941e-9c63f4a0eefb", "value": "Canadian-built, single-engine, high-wing transport and communications aircraft converted from a civilian model. Metal-framed with fabric covering, saw service in 1944-5. Was capable of being equipped with wheels, floats or skis."}

{"id": "61056731-3296-45c9-a35d-ea40b97e139b", "value": "Single-engine, testbed monoplane built to Air Ministry Specification 43/37. Only twelve were produced, the first of which tested the Sabre I engine in 1940, and were used throughout the war. The cockpit could seat two observers behind the pilot."}

{"id": "07c06db4-a1ac-4cf8-8c0a-494fdfd6e1d3", "value": "Wood and fabric transport glider, twenty of which were produced with twin Bristol Mercury engines. Fitted with a hinged nose for loading and unloading, this was the largest glider used by the RAF and could accomodate a 7-ton tank."}

{"id": "e203b7f7-1290-4aeb-85a3-bcb4966beb32", "value": "Two-seat, single-engine, advanced-pilot trainer. Square-winged and fitted with dual controls, this popular trainer was used by British Commonwealth, as well as American and Canadian, air forces."}

{"id": "5005da14-73fa-4b36-b245-3c999121bbb5", "value": "A twin-engined development of the JU88, the JU188 had a higher service ceiling and greater maximum speed. JU188s operated over the UK from 1944 onwards as night intruders and reconnaissance aircraft."}

{"id": "65b59a3b-efdb-4525-9878-d740d6e241aa", "value": "An American turbojet fighter-bomber aircraft. The F-84 was the first production fighter aircraft to utilize in-flight refuelling and the first fighter capable of carrying a nuclear weapon. Designed by Alexander Kartveli, 1946."}

{"id": "cc70a9df-1947-496b-9410-fd4f925e253f", "value": "American, single-engine fighter designed for operation from US Naval aircraft carriers. The Hellcat was a more powerful version of the Wildcat, a total of 1000 being provided to the Fleet Air Arm under Lend-Lease."}

{"id": "ec113940-c23f-43a8-8e98-5ece49e66d91", "value": "Twin-engined, six-crew, heavy bomber. Conceived as a rival to the Lancaster and Flying Fortress, the HE177 was dogged by mechanical and structural problems. Of a thousand produced, only about two hundred saw action."}

{"id": "3ca943a2-7037-4c56-b722-16ee72de6824", "value": "Long-range, four-engine reconnaissance-bomber. Initially produced as a transport, converted and used against Allied convoys in the Channel and the Atlantic. Also served as a VIP transport, one of which was the Immelmann III: Hitler's personal aircraft."}

{"id": "3bb0e3fa-40d9-4813-8970-956f08b2f245", "value": "British multi-purpose, single-engined monoplane that served as a torpedo-bomber, dive-bomber, reconnaissance aircraft and in other roles. Equipped with folding wings for use aboard aircraft carriers."}

{"id": "88500e52-1d82-409c-a49e-3c7f9b4140ea", "value": "Single-engine, single-seat fighter, also adapted as a night-fighter, fighter-bomber, rocket-projectile fighter and tank-buster. The first monoplane to enter RAF service with 14,000 being produced between 1937 and 1944."}

{"id": "ba1cb236-9cf3-45fb-b0b2-7ad2f108d4ce", "value": "Twin-engined fighter-bomber. All metal in construction, entered service in 1940. Supported bombing operations and participated in attacks on France, but not widely used due to engine faults."}

{"id": "b04b5bf0-da65-4a63-ad87-5366995f649f", "value": "A transonic jet fighter, first introduced by North American Aviation in 1947. Best known as the United States's first swept wing fighter. Total production at 9,860 units. Important fighter aircraft in the Korean War. Retired in 1994 (Bolivia)."}

{"id": "d21757bd-051d-401a-a543-5e20d893c705", "value": "Single-engine, single-seat, long range fighter originally designed in 1940 to a British requirement. Outstanding low-level speed and range resulted in its assignment to the ground support (Army co-operation) role."}

{"id": "713cb126-88c7-4b13-b027-c77c2c9b0fba", "value": "Principal glider-pilot training glider fitted with tandem seats. Spruce and plywood in construction, the Hotspur served with the Glider Pilot Regiment between 1941 and 1945."}

{"id": "0012b747-e9ed-433b-bdc4-3c45dc6f8359", "value": "Seven/eight-crew, heavy night-bomber. The first four-engine bomber to join the RAF, with a bomb load of 14000 lb, entered service in 1940. Superseded as a bomber by the Lancaster and Halifax, later versions served as transports and tugs."}

{"id": "e404029d-d840-4274-b710-831b4217925c", "value": "A fighter version of the SKUA fitted with a four-gun turret. The majority were converted to target tugs for use by the RAF and Fleet Air Arm."}

{"id": "176e3e51-311a-4683-8015-48117c294fba", "value": "Twin-engined, single-seat fighter-bomber. Flown by USAAF fighter groups from 1942, excelled as a ground-support fighter. Could carry two 1600 lb bombs or rocket projectiles."}

{"id": "f50004f2-8a2b-482f-ad04-4fde399b547d", "value": "Three-crew, single-engine carrierborne torpedo-bomber. Entered service in 1942, first seeing action during the Battle of Midway. Served with the US Navy until 1956."}

{"id": "bff31222-68e9-4231-ac6b-27307edac0b1", "value": "Four-engined heavy bomber, developed by Avro from the twin-engined Manchester. Entered service in 1942 as the RAF's principal night bomber and took part in the 1,000 bomber raids as well as the famous Dam Busters raid."}

{"id": "e33ae7a3-cab1-482c-813a-eac727247f9a", "value": "Twin-engined air/sea rescue and anti-submarine patrol aircraft. Originally developed from the Wellington and intended as a bomber, entered RAF Coastal Command service in 1943. Fitted with a Leigh Light and ASV radar."}

{"id": "3ca26db5-1269-4a99-8ccb-9f571fba875d", "value": "Single engine, two-crew shipboard reconnaissance and patrol seaplane. Entered service in 1939, this was the last combat floatplane built in Europe."}

{"id": "a380b3e1-21a6-424a-9d8a-b0d3e5a6b108", "value": "Single-engine aircraft designed as a dive-bomber. Found to be inadequate in this role, a number of those delivered to the RAF were used as target tugs. Entered service in 1941."}
{"id": "d58daf09-374e-41da-bc46-a1939f548bb2", "value": "Originally designed as a light bomber but diverted for use as a high speed target tug to replace out-dated biplanes."}

{"id": "2015b43b-dc98-466d-8da8-ef2863d2c9db", "value": "Single-engine, advanced-pilot trainer used in secondary flying training schools. Serving from 1939-50, was also used as a target tug for gunnery practice."}

{"id": "77ad4169-c6bf-4108-af5c-1a02cb91b4a8", "value": "Single-seat fighter-bomber with a single, midships engine and tricycle landing gear. After proving a failure as an air-combat fighter, was used mainly in the ground attack role."}

{"id": "99069b16-afcd-4158-8a52-c5c3774d1690", "value": "Single-engine fighter/dive-bomber. The Fleet Air Arm's first operational monoplane, and its first aircraft to shoot down an enemy during the war."}

{"id": "6e443be5-8445-4cdd-a362-14a314f32d87", "value": "Miles M.14 Magister. Single-engine, two-crew training and communications aircraft. Spruce and plywood in construction, with open cockpits and a fixed landing gear, served between 1937 and 1945."}

{"id": "eb47e543-e82b-4440-9faa-5f39f6fe0400", "value": "American, four-engine, long range, heavy strategic bomber. Entered service in 1943 and used exclusively against Japanese forces. The B29s Enola Gay and Bock's Car were used to drop atomic bombs on Hiroshima and Nagasaki in 1945."}

{"id": "41384934-4b9f-4436-9cf6-87a5953b7cd0", "value": "Four-engine, ten-crew, long-range maritime reconnaissance and anti-submarine aircraft. Developed from the Short C-class Empire airliner. All metal in construction, entered RAF Coastal Command service in 1938."}

{"id": "59b84f54-5211-4604-9503-7082bdfe01b6", "value": "Single-engine, two-crew fighter, also used for convoy escort and reconnaissance. Designed to operate from aircraft carriers. Entered service with the Fleet Air Arm in 1940 and remained in use until 1945."}

skos:ConceptScheme.dcterms:description: {"id": "698d6397-4379-4e13-bd4e-29a06643760c", "value": "Indexing terminology for the recording of aircraft remains and crash sites, listing aircraft types by form (eg. Monoplane, Biplane), function (eg. Fighter, Bomber) and manufacturer (e.g. Atlas, Target, Westland)."}
skos:ConceptScheme.dcterms:title: {"id": "a3b93f5e-1e0c-4061-9ee8-27159e3fc53c", "value": "FISH Historic Aircraft Type"}

skos:Concept.skos:scopeNote: {"id": "2e901e8b-5b12-4426-a316-54ad171b91a6", "value": "Six-crew, twin-engined medium night-bomber. Entered service in 1938 and was the RAF's principal bomber until 1943, participating in the first bombing raid of the war. Later versions served as torpedo and reconnaissance-bombers, transports and trainers."}
{"id": "3ea879c8-1741-42c9-a7ef-e73b542b42dd", "value": "Single-engine, spruce and plywood, fabric-covered training and communications low-wing monoplane. Served from 1939 to 1950."}

{"id": "17b7829d-6100-4ca8-85cb-89c0e76ae129", "value": "US Navy version of the four-engined, six-crew B24 heavy bomber. Modified for long-range reconnaissance duty and used as a patrol-bomber against shipping and submarines."}

{"id": "0c72d1c8-c401-4949-ba86-5b3c5c51dcaa", "value": "Single-engine, single-seat carrierborne fighter: a Spitfire VB fitted with an arrester hook. Modifications on later versions included folding wings, rocket-assisted take-off gear and conversion for photo-reconnaissance duties."}

{"id": "1ebabcb4-c8f3-4e06-8a52-04b38ef5f4f6", "value": "Four-crew, twin-engined monoplane designed as a torpedo-bomber and reconnaissance aircraft for RAF Coastal Command. Withdrawn from operations in November 1940 and downgraded to a trainer."}

{"id": "744e1399-ac87-4e91-9ec4-d2beaee7d1ce", "value": "British twin-engined light/medium bomber developed from the model 142 civil transport. Noted for its speed, this three-crew monoplane had an all-metal, stressed skin structure and a 1000lb bomb load."}

{"id": "fc6ab5bc-8e59-440c-ad0b-97e0eb1aa838", "value": "Developed from the ill-fated ME210, the ME410 Hornisse entered service in May 1943. Although underpowered as a day fighter the ME410 saw service over the UK as a night fighter from 1943-45."}

{"id": "56f5ba97-1191-4330-b7a0-1489f7c5aca8", "value": "Twin-engined monoplane that served the RAF as an advanced trainer and flying ambulance. Mk. I featured a gun turret and served for gunnery and bombing-crew training. Subsequent versions used for pilot, radio and navigation training."}
{"id": "cd82ba50-901b-4a4a-a4e4-09e449266293", "value": "German three-engined air/sea rescue and transport flying boat. Entered service in 1940 as a replacement for the DO18."}
{"id": "ea45f4f7-fe1b-45c0-aa13-c66f9a48e61c", "value": "Twin-engined monoplane originally designed as a reconnaissance aircraft, but also widely used as a trainer. Entered RAF service in 1936."}

{"id": "d42f5bc1-e710-4f49-9b17-053849ec7bf5", "value": "A single engine two seat cabin monoplane tourer, first flown in 1933 as a successor to the Puss Moth. Impressed into military sevice in WWII by the RAF and the Fleet Air Arm as a liaison and communications aircraft, also used by training units."}

{"id": "7c1ce042-4950-4e34-a563-73fb12613db8", "value": "Single-engine, single-seat fighter-bomber. Designed to replace the Hurricane as an interceptor, excelled as a rocket-projectile-firing ground-attack fighter. Entered RAF service in 1941."}

{"id": "777f3f8a-90dc-4430-b7b0-6b3e062ff15d", "value": "Three-seat tactical support aircraft. Entering service with the US 9th Air Force in 1944, the Invader had a bomb load of 4,000 lbs and was later used as a conventional medium bomber."}

{"id": "d35d5e1b-1223-46ae-9733-9aab4dd64ae7", "value": "Six-crew, medium-range, twin-engined reconnaissance flying-boat. Entered service with 209 Squadron in 1939 but, due to design and operation problems, saw little action and was not produced in large numbers."}

{"id": "809d7d4a-5bf7-4430-8389-71d719223abf", "value": "Transport version of the four-engined Lancaster bomber. Serving from 1943 to 1951, and all metal in construction, this aircraft was used extensively during the Berlin airlift."}
{"id": "d66d23f3-7329-45bf-baef-6b4f86134f9f", "value": "American, four-engined, long range, medium/heavy day bomber. Produced in greater numbers than any other American aircraft during the war."}

{"id": "3c2f1111-6bdb-45f4-bcd5-729b055e1ecd", "value": "Single-engine, single-seat fighter-bomber developed from the Typhoon and the abandoned Tornado. Entered service in 1944 with its greatest success being in destroying V.1. flying bombs. One of the fastest World War 2 aircraft, with a top speed of 436 mph."}

{"id": "ecdcc2d8-41ef-40fb-bbcb-24347094ad90", "value": "American twin-engined medium bomber and ground-attack aircraft that entered service in 1941. A small number were delivered to the RAF under the British designation Mitchell I."}

{"id": "05ca9aa6-da7b-4dac-89b3-07b0307e5949", "value": "Originally a light day-bomber, the Boston II, re-christened the Havoc, was adapted for night-flying in the fighter-intruder role. Was capable of a top speed in excess of 300 mph."}

{"id": "e5f96613-7b4a-4c8d-be31-6752d6c465c5", "value": "American-built, twin-engined flying-boat designed for maritime patrol and reconnaissance. Entered US Naval service in 1936 as the PBY-1; christened the Catalina by the RAF, who used it from 1939 on."}

{"id": "e78efcc2-cf27-4963-8642-6528597a024a", "value": "Single-engine, single-seat interceptor fighter developed from the race-winning Schneider Trophy seaplanes. One of the most famous of all combat aircraft, entered RAF service in 1938 and was still in use in the 1950s."}

{"id": "c64d0174-178c-4c58-9e2e-de48123ecc4f", "value": "Twin-engined, medium bomber with a 1200 mile range and a bomb load in excess of 10,000 lb. Entered service in 1940, but engine faults resulted in retirement in 1942 with its design later modified into the acclaimed four-engine Lancaster bomber."}

{"id": "a70da860-8d5b-41f7-96df-c541905e8ee7", "value": "A photo- reconnaissance variant of the Boeing Superfortress, used from 1944, initally deployed in the Pacific war, later for Cold war duties over Europe."}
{"id": "f6545ce7-22a0-41b8-97b4-521675250252", "value": "British three-seat, single-engine light bomber. All metal in construction, this monoplane had a 1000 lb bomb load."}

{"id": "7d1580db-4720-4c9c-8926-f00e6d8b234d", "value": "Four-seat, twin-engined medium bomber. Entered service in 1938. After serving Bomber Command from 1939-42, was converted to a torpedo-bomber and mine-layer with RAF Coastal Command."}

{"id": "28a2ddc6-578e-40b5-a053-5da5eff6fe8f", "value": "Single-engine, two-crew multi-role aircraft designed for RAF Army co-operation. Entered RAF service in 1938. Noted for its role dropping agents into Europe, also served as a night-fighter, day ground-attack aircraft and target tug."}

{"id": "51c088e2-1c27-48cc-be05-bcb3a314d314", "value": "British two-seat, twin-engined night fighter. Also used for roles such as long-range escort fighter, ground-attack and anti-shipping strike aircraft, bomber, torpedo-carrier and rocket fighter."}

{"id": "51220762-e254-4cbc-b9f1-d10d5b900bb6", "value": "Dutch aircraft manufacturer named after its founder, Anthony Fokker. Set up in 1912 in Schwerin, Germany, moving to the Netherlands in 1919. The world's largest aircraft manufacturer in the late 1920s."}

{"id": "f019449d-2a0e-4ac7-8435-f9e65552b500", "value": "A streamlined, twin-engined bomber, the DO17 entered service in 1937 with the Condor Legion, having started life as a high-speed mail and passenger transport aircraft, a role for which it was ill-suited due to the narrowness of the fuselage."}

{"id": "da701590-dbe6-4ecd-a3de-843a181986c5", "value": "Also known as the C-47 Skytrain, this twin-engined, military transport was developed from the DC-3 twenty-eight-seat commercial airliner and was the most extensively employed transport of the Second World War."}

{"id": "96a6b95f-aae4-45e5-bd64-2aa50511c058", "value": "A single-engine, photo-reconnaissance fighter designed for operation from aircraft carriers. Later adapted as a night fighter, it entered service in 1943 and remained in production until 1956."}
{"id": "859bcdd0-1217-4ed0-bc72-215c847cd439", "value": "All-weather fighter/interceptor first flow in 1951, introduced into service in 1956 and retired from the RAF in 1968."}

{"id": "eb754cf1-415d-47a8-8175-684b51bf8433", "value": "A British six-seat single-engined light aircraft, built by Airspeed Limited. First flew in 1933, saw some use as an airliner. The first British type with a retractable undercarriage. Designed by Hessell Tiltman (co-founder). 16 Couriers built."}

{"id": "8ac3f1b9-9295-4e83-91ec-19b71a70878e", "value": "A tandem two-seat, twin-engined, all-weather, long-range supersonic jet interceptor fighter/fighter-bomber originally developed for the United States Navy by McDonnell Aircraft.It first entered service in 1960 with the U.S. Navy."}

{"id": "cb8cb1b7-6ce6-454c-ad0d-d8b4ee0e50a2", "value": "German single-engine, four-seat maritime patrol and reconnaissance flying-boat. In production between 1934 and 1940, the DO18 was replaced by the three engined DO24."}

{"id": "d1c67a92-f99b-4a79-bde1-f44c63fed067", "value": "Second World War allied patrol-bomber built by Lockheed Vega, a Lockheed subsidiary. This aircraft was a military development of the Lodestar, USAF designation B-34."}

{"id": "0b6b8e8a-b2ad-4d90-bc73-315245758ff0", "value": "Single-engine, three-crew torpedo-spotter, reconnaissance and anti-submarine biplane. Entered Naval service in 1936, designed for operation from aircraft carriers and equipped with folding wings."}

{"id": "e1a4c872-3b7c-47b0-99c6-172eda0548cd", "value": "A single-engine, two-crew biplane day bomber and general purpose aircraft, developed from the IIIF (some of which were converted into Gordons) and first flown in 1931."}

{"id": "797fab30-0bb6-47fe-b1be-d4130efa6412", "value": "A biplane torpedo-bomber designed to be flown from aircraft carriers. Equipped with foldable wings for ease of storage. Joined Fleet Air Arm service in 1940, intended as a replacement for the Swordfish."}

{"id": "e06ed30f-d9e2-45bf-8e49-b3ce815eab79", "value": "Single-engine, two or three-crew pre-World War 2 biplane fighter and general purpose aircraft. First flown in 1931, the Seal was a Naval variant on the Fairey Gordon and a forerunner of the Swordfish."}

{"id": "833d0faf-d446-4386-926a-62d3107435bb", "value": "The Fairey Aviation Co. Ltd., established 1916 by Sir Richard Fairey. During WW2 formed a group production scheme with Blackburn Aircraft, Ltd. and Boulton Paul Aircraft, Ltd.."}
{"id": "245d1051-4204-45eb-bf93-524b21cff2af", "value": "British, single-engined, light day bomber biplane. Built in 1923, this was the RAF's first interbellum designed day bomber."}

{"id": "526e807d-5249-44de-b38f-684372cb1ec0", "value": "A civil passenger transport biplane produced by the Farman Aviation Works from 1919. Instrumental in the creation of early airlines and commercial routes in Europe after World War I. Initially designed in 1918 as a heavy bomber. Some 60 units built."}

{"id": "fc6c59d2-7671-41e5-8b5c-ca9dc40cefc8", "value": "Farman Aviation Works was an aircraft company founded and run by the brothers Richard, Henri, and Maurice Farman in 1908. The firm made pusher biplane aircraft for military and training purposes, it was eventually dissolved in 1956."}

{"id": "7c879078-ab62-4984-bf6f-5d15d5e26f35", "value": "Twin-engine, three-crew, long-range heavy bomber biplane. Entered service in 1917. Of wooden construction with a fabric covering, the Vimy was fitted with a skid under the nose of its fuselage to prevent tipping forward upon landing."}
{"id": "030b2229-1b51-4b23-987a-9565becaa0eb", "value": "Twin-engined, four-crew bomber. Wooden framed, with linen covering, entered service in 1924, equipping several RAF squadrons."}

{"id": "08185dfb-7800-4c37-b99d-89bf34b285d9", "value": "Vickers (Aviation) Ltd. formed in 1911, as the aviation division of Vickers Ltd., and took control of Supermarine Aviation Works Ltd. the same year. Taken over by Vickers-Armstrongs Ltd. in 1938."}
{"id": "668aecd6-4954-4a07-aba0-68837f3ca877", "value": "A Mark 6B aircraft which has undergone further modifications to enhance performance or armament."}

{"id": "a2b649cf-b298-47d0-9750-6d35581e8963", "value": "An important two-seat, tractor biplane, initially used by the RFC in a reconnaissance role and by the RNAS as a bomber. Later converted to a single-seat Home Defence fighter and ultimately used as a trainer."}
{"id": "4a9482d3-3f20-4b2e-bd4f-fb6277c445d6", "value": "A single-engine, heavy, long range, three to five-crew day bomber. Served only with 99 Squadron RAF, 1924-5."}

{"id": "f1539263-c1b5-4de8-8ea7-8f51fd910969", "value": "A two-seat trainer chosen to replace the Avro 504. 380 entered RAF service with many finding their way onto the civilian market at the end of their careers."}

{"id": "8e0cc89c-c1da-4630-a26a-cf010856dd64", "value": "A. V. Roe & Co., Ltd. formed in 1909. A subsidiary of the Hawker Siddeley Aircraft Co., Ltd. from 1935, having formerly been a member of the Siddeley group. Produced such notable aircraft as the Lancaster, the York and the Anson."}

{"id": "e44ad4e9-6b16-43fc-8cba-5bdc9676a415", "value": "A biplane, reconnaissance aircraft with a crew of 3 or 4 which equipped 3 and 22 squadrons RAF before passing to the Fleet Air Arm. Produced in two variants."}

{"id": "28a067da-b5dd-4185-8454-c44da31bd289", "value": "A jet-powered tailless delta wing high-altitude strategic bomber plane, operated by the RAF from 1956 until 1984. Typically armed with nuclear weapons but capable of conventional bombing missions. Used as a nuclear deterrent in the Cold War."}

{"id": "d1bb7eb5-c25f-467a-9a49-12fdb17b9c49", "value": "Single-seat, single-engine biplane fighter. In operational service from 1939 to 1941, this was the last, and believed to be the best, biplane to be flown in the RAF. All-metal in construction with fabric and aluminium covering."}
{"id": "7493743d-648a-4d30-ba98-a61e303440da", "value": "A pilotless aircraft armed with explosives and fuelled to stall over its intended target."}
{"id": "ba104718-558d-4c4d-a3d6-dd5fc84062d6", "value": "An engineless aeroplane, designed to be towed aloft, that travels suspended by upward air currents."}
{"id": "ef4f4a71-de03-474e-aca7-c1029d5c08c1", "value": "An aeroplane with two wings, or planes, placed one above the other either side of the fuselage."}
{"id": "da6d5f67-f308-4c92-9cca-722d5f37b17e", "value": "Aircraft grouped according to their physical form."}
{"id": "10e0ad31-b5c2-4f34-b50a-18092e262620", "value": "Generally understood to mean aircraft whose normal loaded weight is less than 2750kg (6060 lb)."}

{"id": "c7d40f63-1dd4-49b7-a1e4-9c7eb6d6e43a", "value": "An aircraft lifted by gas bags, containing hydrogen or helium, but propelled by engines. Also known as a dirigible balloon, firm and streamlined in shape and incapable of high speeds. Used extensively during World War One."}

{"id": "c1ac80fe-01bb-4608-823a-de702414d95d", "value": "An aircraft designed to land on water. They can be divided into 2 types: Flying boats (designed with a hull allowing the aircraft to land directly on water) and Floatplanes (where the undercarriage was replaced by fixed floats)."}
{"id": "a8d8fecf-0271-447f-99a6-271063677f94", "value": "An aeroplane featuring three wings, or planes, placed one above the other either side of its fuselage."}

{"id": "dcfada65-26ae-4d30-ba36-80652bf36913", "value": "A French airliner produced in 1925. A four-engined biplane developed from the Bleriot 115 and 135 but larger than these. Two were built for Air Union (the Paris-London route). Both crashed with fatalaties in 1926 (Kent)."}
{"id": "459f8ddc-0119-4220-8125-0bb8f1471687", "value": "A Mark 1B aircraft which has undergone further modification to enhance performance or armament."}

{"id": "88ffdd11-d27a-454f-9b04-ec7c350e7f52", "value": "The Consolidated Vultee Aircraft Corporation. Formed in 1943 with the merging of The Consolidated Aircraft Corporation and Vultee Aircraft, Inc.."}

{"id": "bc50932a-4052-4b03-8574-fba3ca7672d9", "value": "A German aircraft manufacturer of the 1930s and 1940s, pre-war the company were noted for making sailplanes and sports planes; during the Second World War they made military aircraft including flying bombs."}

{"id": "977909cd-4ff4-469e-96c2-b87df0bde9a5", "value": "Chance Vought Division of the United Aircraft Corporation. Was reconstituted as a separate division in 1943, after being part of the Vought-Sikorsky division, to concentrate on the production of combat aircraft."}

{"id": "d27b3ba5-c66d-4f76-bdd7-9b0983081e62", "value": "The Republic Aviation Corporation. Developed from the Seversky Aircraft Corporation, founded by Alexander P. de Seversky in 1931 after the collapse of his previous company, the Seversky Aero Corporation, in the 1929 stock market crash."}

{"id": "08b03bfd-ab49-4723-89e0-bcfd20640be0", "value": "Gothauer Waggonfabrik A.G., based in Gotha, Thuringia (Germany). During World War 2 produced mostly training and light commercial aircraft and troop and freight-carrying gliders."}

{"id": "17521e73-d09a-481d-b5a8-fe9ab8a94792", "value": "Sir W. G. Armstrong Whitworth Aircraft, Ltd. formed in 1921. Controlled by the Armstrong Siddeley Development Co., Ltd., a subsidiary of the Hawker Siddeley Aircraft Co., Ltd. from 1935. Pioneers in the development of all-metal aircraft."}
{"id": "31d3d1a2-5655-4259-afec-0275f6a9e768", "value": "Beech Aircraft Corporation, also known as Beechcraft, established 1932"}
{"id": "a5bae719-aa26-4cfd-ad28-901d935cd59c", "value": "Aircraft grouped according to their manufacturer."}

{"id": "5a4643e1-1418-4471-bef8-01c8df37530b", "value": "The Percival Aircraft Company was formed in 1932 and re-organized as Percival Aircraft Ltd. in 1937, when the works moved from Gravesend to Luton."}
{"id": "0095cb1d-4a35-4673-8972-ba0b2c924a82", "value": "A US aircraft manufacturer. The Cessna Aircraft Co Inc was established in 1927"}

{"id": "59d85af7-e830-4539-9d92-51e667ceaaa0", "value": "Formed in 1935 by Lawrence D. Bell, Ray P. Whitman and Robert J. Woods, who left the Consolidated Aircraft Corporation when it moved its factory from Buffalo to San Diego. Sub-contracted work before its first original design, the XFM-1, in 1937."}

{"id": "3d33ed31-d2c5-4021-b3b2-6dee318d54ae", "value": "The Brewster Aeronautical Corporation was founded in 1932, taking over the plant, equipment, designs and goodwill of Brewster & Co., Inc.'s aircraft division. Initially manufacturing seaplane components, later designed and produced complete aircraft."}

{"id": "35873348-05ab-48ab-87c5-c5d6c4aa3599", "value": "Junkers Flugzeug und Motorenwerke, A.G.. Formed in 1910 with Professor Junkers being granted a patent for an all-wing aeroplane. Produced first successful all-metal aeroplane, the Junkers J1, in 1915."}

{"id": "6c7cbee2-32d5-4c8b-8aa2-b153ca64123c", "value": "A French aeroplane company that primarily built racing aircraft before World War I and fighter aircraft during World War I and between the wars. First set up in 1902 as manufacturer of engine components, then aircraft in 1911 as Nieuport et Deplante."}

{"id": "58f35eb9-b15b-48f0-9eb0-e12b2bd67278", "value": "Airspeed (1934) Ltd. registered in 1934 when associated with shipbuilders Swan, Hunter and Wigham Richardson Ltd.. Acquired by de Havilland in 1940, maintaining own identity and changing name to Airspeed Ltd. in 1944."}
{"id": "f8cde3b9-d931-4af1-a4fb-ddb4be202641", "value": "A British aero- and marine-engineering company based on the Isle of Wight specializing in the construction of flying boats."}
{"id": "5901cd16-76b4-4a74-a447-014f06232083", "value": "North American Aviation, Inc., incorporated in Delaware in 1928."}

{"id": "ae04c2c6-a944-4da1-9d78-d818f97a05f2", "value": "The Sopwith Aviation Co., Ltd.. Established in 1911 by the noted aviator Mr T. O. M. Sopwith. Produced many notable aircraft, including the Camel and a Schneider Cup-winning seaplane."}

{"id": "b0309ae0-3c9c-4a09-954c-408441e23cb8", "value": "The Waco Aircraft Company, established in 1921. One of the largest pre-war producers of civil aircraft in America, Waco specialised in the production of troop and cargo carrying gliders during World War Two."}

{"id": "d7a10cab-8e1d-4ba3-b59e-59566ae48ddc", "value": "Miles Aircraft, Ltd., originally known as Phillips & Powis Aircraft Ltd.. Formed in 1935 as a public company to take over aircraft manufacture from Phillips & Powis Aircraft (Reading) Ltd."}

{"id": "0d018ae7-21df-4caf-8c77-73b1b0b1be91", "value": "The Stinson Division of The Consolidated Vultee Aircraft Corporation. Originally the Stinson Aircraft Division of the Aviation Manufacturing Corpn., who were taken over by Vultee Aircraft Inc., who merged with the Consolidated Aircraft Corpn. in 1943."}

{"id": "2f05f180-7e66-4b9c-9af3-0e95fb0a32dd", "value": "Arado Flugzeugwerke. Formed in 1931 in Germany when the aircraft manufacturer Albatros Flugzeugwerke was declared bankrupt and part of it merged with Arado Handells-Gessellschaft."}

{"id": "40ff6770-e658-4c9e-bd95-effb294f20df", "value": "A French aircraft manufacturer founded by Louis Bleriot and Gabriel Voisin, both aviators and inventors, in 1903, dissolved in 1906. After World War I Bleriot founded Bleriot Aeronautique developing commercial aircraft."}

{"id": "10316df8-0582-4121-b0c6-f2e68df02a5c", "value": "Marine Aircraft Experimental Establishment, RAF Felixstowe. Developed seaplanes and flying boats until World War Two, when the establishment moved to Helensburg, Scotland."}

{"id": "3724ab24-2a24-4afe-98c2-02a1d68d1d61", "value": "Vickers-Armstrongs Ltd.. In 1938 took over Vickers (Aviation) Ltd., which itself had taken control of Supermarine Aviation Works Ltd. in 1928."}

{"id": "dcdd02f4-0310-478d-acb9-1183ba9d2ca1", "value": "The Boeing Aircraft Company, established 1916. A subsidiary of The Boeing Airplane Company. Notable aircraft produced include the B17 Flying Fortress and the B29 Superfortress."}
{"id": "94f571bf-e2fa-4a81-abf4-5eda2ef7db42", "value": "The Curtiss-Wright Corporation, Airplane Division, established in 1910. Notable aircraft produced include the Kittyhawk."}

{"id": "af16016b-06ca-4202-8a00-6cca6ac05dce", "value": "Originally the Zeppelin Werk Lindau G.m.b.H., developed metal aircraft from World War One under the guidance of Dr. Ing. Claude Dornier, changing its name to Dornier-Werke G.m.b.H. in 1922."}
{"id": "f582a284-ba26-475b-8e53-18bae8c12274", "value": "Founded by Professor Willy Messerschmitt as the Bayerische Flugzeugwerke. Reconstituted in 1938 as the Messerschmitt A.G.."}

{"id": "c261aa7e-55dd-429c-964b-2e37d2cd7ff7", "value": "Ernst Heinkel A.G.. Formed in 1922 by Dr. Ernst Heinkel, previously Chief Designer with Hansa-Brandenburgische Flugzeugwerke, where he produced many notable seaplanes during World War One."}

{"id": "ce14abfb-3f97-494a-bceb-40c1f9ed4450", "value": "Noorduyn Aviation Limited. Formed in 1934 by Mr R.B.C. Noorduyn as a successor to Noorduyn Aircraft Limited, which was formed in 1933. The company's most notable production aircraft was the Norseman transport."}
{"id": "b6012fbf-27b5-4e57-ba0a-fbb1272b5871", "value": "Westland Aircraft Ltd., formed in 1935 to take over the aircraft branch of Petters Ltd., previously known as the Westland Aircraft Works."}

{"id": "c1f80056-282e-43f9-83a9-948856185f5a", "value": "The Bristol Aeroplane Co., Ltd.. Founded in 1910 by Sir George White, a pioneer of electric tramways. The company had previously been The British and Colonial Aeroplane Co., Ltd.."}

{"id": "21e4cb06-d0f4-4504-bd7d-4f06fb332730", "value": "Blackburn Aircraft, Ltd., founded by Robert Blackburn, who produced his first aircraft in 1910. Specialised in the production of torpedo-carrying aircraft."}
{"id": "d0b81f35-3fca-4dc9-9dd7-69b20a81436e", "value": "Boulton Paul Aircraft, Ltd., formed in 1934 to take over the Aircraft Department of Boulton & Paul, Ltd."}

{"id": "05f00a53-04e5-4cf1-b35a-220af91f85d4", "value": "The English Electric Company Limited. Formed in 1918, but didn't move into aircraft production until 1938, at the Government's request. Continued to develop aircraft after the war and in 1948 produced the `Canberra', Britain's first jet-propelled bomber."}

{"id": "8d60d72e-f40e-4d13-a322-3d5a485cc071", "value": "Formed in 1936 as British Marine Aircraft Ltd. to construct civil flying-boats. In 1937, with the arrival of H P Folland, formerly Chief designer for Gloster Aircraft Co., became Folland Aircraft, Ltd.."}

{"id": "91b7a89f-3fa4-4fd5-8ee7-8625e4d06052", "value": "Hawker Aircraft, Ltd., established 1933 to succeed the H. G. Hawker Engineering Co., Ltd., which had been formed in 1920 as the result of the voluntary liquidation of the renowned Sopwith concern."}

{"id": "605c2a37-ee7d-4070-8180-74d4108dcb53", "value": "McDonnell Douglas was a major American aerospace manufacturer and defense contractor, producing a number of famous commercial and military aircraft."}

{"id": "6a1ac06d-13e1-4f9e-bf7c-73731c1faf83", "value": "Short Bros. (Rochester & Bedford), Ltd. founded by Eustace and Oswald Short in 1898, originally manufacturing spherical balloons. In 1936 became Short & Harland Ltd. in collaboration with Belfast shipbuilders Harland and Wolff."}

{"id": "0e611af9-bbb1-42b4-8df5-015ba63951c0", "value": "Focke-Wulf Flugzeugbau G.m.b.H.. Founded in 1924 and amalgamated in 1931 with the Albatross-Flugzeugwerke G.m.b.H.. Converted to a G.m.b.H. in 1937."}

{"id": "fc18777a-4eda-4fa4-a506-be32db2db25c", "value": "The de Havilland Aircraft Co., Ltd., founded in 1920 by Sir Geoffrey de Havilland, C.B.E., A.F.C., F.R.Ae.S. Originally developers of commercial aircraft, were responsible for such notable wartime aircraft as the Mosquito and the Tiger Moth."}
{"id": "c3331cf4-19bb-42f5-877b-a6179d1a3e94", "value": "General Aircraft Limited."}

{"id": "5a76d0a2-c846-40af-a97d-6ab0fda69a33", "value": "Handley Page, Ltd.. Founded by Sir Frederick Handley Page, this was the first limited company to be incorporated in Great Britain for the purpose of aircraft manufacture."}

{"id": "eb07b08d-a5f0-49d4-a1b9-819f61e47bb0", "value": "The Lockheed Aircraft Corporation. Founded in 1916 by Allen and Malcolm Loughead. In 1926 the company moved to Burbank and changed its name to The Lockheed Aircraft Company, and was then incorporated in 1932."}
{"id": "309ee0a6-55bf-4d6c-9393-eb5bff593ec4", "value": "The Douglas Aircraft Company, Inc., established in 1920, reorganized in 1928. Produced such notable aircraft as the Dakota."}

{"id": "68c30cce-0a5f-4307-9c52-5f436ec23923", "value": "Aircraft Manufacturing Co., Ltd. Established in 1912 by Mr G. Holt Thomas. In 1914 secured the services of Capt. Geoffrey de Havilland as designer-in-chief, who went on to lend his initials to a number of highly successful machines."}

{"id": "2ef09e45-eac1-4d65-893f-a9d070938d7c", "value": "Gloster Aircraft Co., Ltd. formed in 1917, later became part of the Hawker Siddeley Group. First British or American company to design, build and fly a jet-propelled aircraft."}
{"id": "8d2f6512-2c27-4656-9bba-3bb100ec2c38", "value": "The Grumman Aircraft Engineering Corporation founded by Leroy R Grumman and incorporated in 1929."}

{"id": "bffa275b-b8f0-4e19-aa5a-a7e929e3141b", "value": "The Glenn L. Martin Company, established in 1909 by Glenn L Martin. Produced the first successful American-designed twin-engined aeroplane, the Martin Twin, which was then converted for use as a passenger aircraft."}
{"id": "1372d58b-20f0-4f1d-af60-fb4b24182b48", "value": "Aircraft grouped according to their function."}
{"id": "9a50b8fe-620f-4d5d-a16a-dc469cd32958", "value": "Used to identify the variations of an aircraft. Index with Manufacturer, Form and Function."}
{"id": "de393747-9b7e-484c-944d-4cdcc3bae151", "value": "Types of aircraft to aid the recording of aircraft remains and crash sites, listing aircraft by form, function and manufacturer."}
{"id": "97fcc93f-9c19-4663-b39b-763af17bf3c1", "value": "An aircraft used for the towing of targets."}
{"id": "c7129a11-d680-45f2-a0c2-273c0845a81b", "value": "An aircraft used for towing gliders aloft."}
{"id": "6d52e7e2-c0b7-44c7-aa13-0939737ad933", "value": "An aircraft used for towing another aircraft or object, such as a glider or target."}
{"id": "ee407631-7480-413a-b042-9736f1e975a2", "value": "High speed, short to medium-range bomber, usually powered by two engines."}
{"id": "f18d82f7-c725-45da-8903-35006bceca79", "value": "An aircraft equipped to deploy explosive mines."}

{"id": "450495e1-8a2a-4d4a-bcaf-958549ce069e", "value": "Large, three-engined, long range reconnaissance flying boat. Wooden hull and frame construction, with linen covering. Entered service in 1930."}

{"id": "a6ef5c74-88f7-4cc1-8a2c-841c7c2cc701", "value": "Three/four-crew, single-engine, shipboard observation and air/sea rescue amphibian seaplane. Entered RAF service in 1936. Also employed for gunnery spotting, anti-submarine and convoy protection duties."}

{"id": "f99fe306-48d2-4fac-a1d4-4834df12e743", "value": "Interbellum, twin-engined, five-crew, biplane flying-boat with a characteristic triple tail-fin. Entered service in 1925 and used for general reconnaissance duties. The Mk.I had a wooden fuselage, whilst the Mk.II's was metal in construction."}

{"id": "114fb8c2-9b4c-4402-ba0e-383a597d07ff", "value": "Four-crew, twin-engined, general reconnaissance flying-boat. Entered service after World War One, becoming the RAF's standard flying-boat until replaced by the Supermarine Southampton in 1925."}

{"id": "8463e8c3-c2b0-4402-ac79-f0acf87c5867", "value": "Twin-engined, seven-crew, coastal reconnaissance, biplane flying-boat. Designed to the same specification as the Saro London, entered service in 1937. Also serving in an anti-submarine role, was replaced by the Consolidated Canso (Catalina) in 1943."}

{"id": "39aed2a2-3303-4aba-a873-4ca3c4c4b3d2", "value": "An aeroplane with the capability to land at sea, the underside of its fuselage shaped like the hull of a sea-going vessel and designed to make contact with the water."}
